headline: CNN This Morning
subHeadline: JPMorgan CEO Jamie Dimon Weighs In On SVB's Collapse; Unemployment Rate Drops To 3.5 percent, Still Historic Low; Jeremy Renner Speaks About Horror Of Snowplow Accident. Aired 8:30-9a ET

utterances.speaker: JAMIE DIMON, CEO, JPMORGAN CHASE
utterances.sentences: I believe the regulators could have forced it. If my regulators called me up and said we do not like X and you have to change it, I would change it.

utterances.speaker: POPPY HARLOW, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: You would. There's a-

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: There was no law change that made that not possible.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: There's a 2021 regulation change that that would said that this was just guidance. So you're saying it should be forced.

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: No, it wasn't just guidance.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: I have this guidance too. But when they told me I have to do it, I'm going to do it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You do it. You do it.

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: I'm going to do it, yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: So let's talk about regulation, you say better regulation would not have prevented?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: No, no, it would have.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: It would have so what's better?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Oh I think, again, we have liquidity, discount windows, we have mortgage laws, we've got capital laws, we've got TLAC laws, we've got how you can use the discount window. There are 100 rules. I'm saying thoughtfully adjust the mix of how you do those, make a bit of changes. If you have uninsured deposits with that means held to maturity, should you have debt issued? Should the supervisors for something to not statutorily, not voluntarily.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. DIMON

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You write in your annual letter about what you call your word, Whack-a-mole, you seem to like that word and politically motivated responses to the banking crisis? Like what?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Like no, I think very often, when it comes to regulations, you have, this is the problem, they try to fix that, but it often has unintended consequences. If you want healthy regional banks, community banks, you should also listen to them about what excess cost does to their ability to compete.You know, what extra high court debt does to it, and have a thoughtful conversation about what are the things we can do to make it easier for you and make the system safer? I believe that that's doable. It's not doable without the conversation. And without the analysis.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: I was reading back some things you said in 2008. And this was in the middle of the crisis, you just acquired Bear Stearns in a fire sale, trying to stabilize banking system. And then you said, if you don't worry in this business, you're crazy. What are you most worried about right now?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Two things? Well, I think (inaudible) quantitative tightening, the effect that has on long term rates, inflation higher for longer, that's kind of the tide going out. So even when Bear Stearns went down, you think other people have seen that and said, I have too much leverage, too much mortgage debt, too much this and made some changes.Lehman went down six months later, I think they might have been able to fix that in the meantime. So that's a little bit of a warning to people like, but I think this war in Ukraine, or I think that is changing everything we think about the world, how we should think about safety and security, even around food, energy, it's changing economic relationships. (inaudible) in the relationship with us and China. That is the most important thing. I mean, if you want to have a free and democratic Western world, and an American Century in the next 100 century, that's what we got to focus on.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You said last year on that front, the autocratic world thinks that the western world is a little lazy, and incompetent. And there's a little bit of truth to that. Is that still how you see it?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Yes, I think you know, I think we do a lot of things that - we're in great position. So for the American public, we have food, water, energy, we're the most prosperous nation the world's ever seen, that's still true, the most innovative.Just go to Atlanta, go to - not some people just in Silicon Valley, but towards Atlanta, towards New York, towards Brooklyn. You know, it's all over the place, we have the high - GDP per person is $70,000, plus, China's is $15,000. They import 10 million barrels of oil a day. They don't have the Atlantic in the Pacific, they have a very complicated neighborhood. They're, you know, they're aiming their neighbors, they're all starting to rearm. We've got a great hand. On the other hand, we haven't done a pretty good job taking care of our lower paid citizens or inner-city schools, immigration, taxation and I think people should pay their taxes, litigation, which you know, it costs 1 percent of GDP. And if it was, if it created more fairness in life, I'd say that was good, but it's capricious, arbitrary, slow, you know. And so I can go on and on about mortgages, affordable, you worry about affordable housing. You know, we all agree with that. But very often the problem with affordable housing isn't capital, it's local zoning laws. So if America just got up its own way, I think we can grow at 3 percent a year.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Are you worried about how close Iran, Russia and China are to one another right now and are getting to one another? Do you think about that? You're a student of history?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: I mean, if you were going to ally with the Western world, America and Europe, Western World War or you're going to ally with Iran and Russia? I mean, please, am I worried? Not really.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: That doesn't worry?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: That worries some of our top generals.

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: OK. You said military? Yes, you should worry about geopolitics. But I just told you what a great hand America has. Same with kind of Europe, what we should be doing is allies - making sure we're the allies, not just militarily, but economically, strategically, diplomacy, development, finance, you know, have the rest of the world want to join us.So if you're India, would you rather be part of that group, or part of the Western world?

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Are we doing enough to entice.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Should the FDIC insure more than $250,000? Because I think a lot of people feel right now after what we've seen that every deposit is just insured with no ceiling.

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: You know, I think probably, but it goes back to my thing about regulations. If you do this, you don't need to do that. If you do this, you don't need to do that. If you do them both, you can hurt. So just be very thoughtful. Probably we should raise the deposit.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: To what?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: I don't know yet. I mean, again, you got to do the analysis in that.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: What about--

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: But I think that would help community banks.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: It would help raise it? OK. So final question on that. Should the - should banks like yours, the big guys with the most assets that have an implicit guarantee that you're essentially not going to fail pay a higher percentage into deposit insurance?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Oh, God, I don't know. I'll leave that to people.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You have no opinion on that?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: If you guys should pay more or not.

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Well, if we were too big to fail, by the way, our bonds wouldn't trade the way they trade just so you know, and you were in the markets and so.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Fair. OK, talk about the economy. You wrote a lot about this in your annual letter. Has this banking crisis, even though you think it's almost over which I'm really glad to hear, though increased chances of a recession here?

utterances.speaker: DIMON
utterances.sentences: Yes. But I look at it like it's not definitive. It's just like another weight on the scale. And think of it as you know, people who says like raising rates of 50 basis points or something like that. We are seeing people reduce lending a little bit, cut back a little bit, pull back a little bit. It won't necessarily force recession, but it is recessionary.(END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Recession more likely, because of this banking crisis from Jamie Dimon.

utterances.speaker: KAITLAN COLLINS, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Not definitive but another weight on the scale.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Interesting way of how he's looking at it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes.

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Over time now to talk about the monthly job numbers. Monthly job report to CNN. CNN's business correspondent, Rahel Solomon is here. Good morning to you. Coming out of Jamie Dimon now, what are you seeing?

utterances.speaker: RAHEL SOLOMON, CNN BUSINESS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: Yes, so this was a cooling job report, but very much in line with expectations. So let's get to the numbers. So we added 236,000 jobs in the month of March, the expectation was 240,000. The unemployment rate ticking down from 3.6 percent to 3.5 percent. Guys, we're back at that fresh 50-year low for unemployment. We saw people come off the sidelines.So the Fed certainly wants to see that. We want to see more workers entering the workforce, because we still have so many jobs. Let's take a look at wages. So wages increased 0.3 percent - 0.3 percent on a monthly basis, 4.2 percent on an annual basis. Where we saw job gains, some of what we've been seeing, right, a continued trend, leisure and hospitality continuing to add jobs there. Government jobs continuing to add jobs there. So this is something that is certainly a cooling. I should say that we haven't seen job growth in this range really in the last few years. So certainly a cooling but I would argue a welcome cooling, certainly for the Fed.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Is it enough?

utterances.speaker: SOLOMON
utterances.sentences: Will it be enough to tame inflation? I mean, I think that's a really tough question to ask. I mean, we'll see. Right? I mean, I think it's--

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: It has to continue.

utterances.speaker: SOLOMON
utterances.sentences: I mean, I think it's a long road ahead.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: And the markets are reacting well to this, right?

utterances.speaker: SOLOMON
utterances.sentences: The markets are actually closed today for the holiday. So I can't tell you about market reaction.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh stocks, I thought stocks were down. But anyways, I didn't know that.

utterances.speaker: SOLOMON
utterances.sentences: Yes, the markets are actually closed. But they do reopen Monday. But what I can tell you is that I would expect that this would be the type of report that investors would like to see, right, because let's put this in context. After the Fed has done so much, right?We've seen nine interest rate hikes since last March. That's a lot. We've hiked rates from about 0 percent to 5 percent in almost a year in just about a year. So investors are looking for and I would argue many consumers are looking for the Fed to stop with the rate hikes, right? I mean, it has sent credit card rates higher, it has sent mortgage rates higher. And so we're hoping for a bit of a break in terms of the rate hikes, will this be enough to get the Fed to cool down? Maybe I mean, Citibank put out a note this morning saying it still expects another rate hike of 25 basis points. Oxford Economics says the same so will it be enough it remains to be seen.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I forgot it was Good Friday.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: See you on May 3rd.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: I forgot it was Good Friday.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. We'll see what they do.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Thank you Rahel.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Thank you Rahel.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Appreciate that.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: All right. Hours of hidden camera footage now appears to show a dermatologist poisoning her husband, with Drano in his lemonade stunning allegations with the details ahead.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: California, California grand jury has just indicted a dermatologist on charges of repeatedly trying to poison her husband with liquid drain cleaner. The attorney for Emily Yu says it was her husband who quote engineered the events during a contentious divorce. The husband says he installed cameras allegedly catching her in the Act.CNN's Camila Bernal is joining us live from Los Angeles Camilla in this case. I know it first came to light last year but we're learning so many details about it. What's the latest?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And so pungent What a bizarre case Camila Bernal, thank you for the latest on that.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: It really is. All right, new details also emerging this morning after the fatal stabbing of Cash App founder Bob Lee. The San Francisco standard is reporting surveillance video and police records indicate that Lee had stab wounds to the chest. They also show that he called 911 for help and tried to flag down a car.(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: JONAH OWEN LAMB, REPORTER, SAN FRANCISCO STANDARD
utterances.sentences: He seems to lift his shirt up as he approaches a car that is stopped in the corner with its flashers on. The car then drives away he falls to the ground. He gets up again and then walks back on main the way he came but on the other side of the street and falls down.(END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: The surveillance photo obtained by The Daily Mail captures some of Bob Lee's final moments as he staggered toward an apartment building with blood on his hands. Police are still trying to identify a suspect in this tragic attack.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh boy. Well, the White House giving a sneak peek at its decorations for this weekend's Easter festivities. How's the rest of the country celebrating Easter and Passover and Passover, Harry Enten is here with this morning's number surrounded by butterflies and an invitation.

utterances.speaker: HARRY ENTEN, CNN SENIOR DATA REPORTER
utterances.sentences: Obviously.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Looking at this morning's number. Holy Week, so what is happening this morning? We have Easter and we have Passover.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Right. So this morning's number is one why because Google searches for Easter this April ranked number one ahead of every other month since 2004. My goodness gracious, I think, probably we're coming out of COVID, right? And the idea is, hey, maybe we can go out there. And we can celebrate with our family.We can go to church, we can have people over for Easter lunch, and, you know, maybe roll some eggs with the kids. Who knows? But it's also Passover. And I heard you were very interested in this, Don.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: And I think you know, we'd spoken about Hanukkah before, right?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Yes, I know about Passover. I just think that we explained to people it's always good to people, to give people knowledge about - about things, right?

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Right. So you know, Passover is right now two. And it's for either seven or eight days and nights depending on who you ask, where you are. A lot of Jews in Israel actually only celebrate for seven days. But here in the States, we celebrate it for eight because we're trying to buffer it because we're not exactly sure when it occurred. It honors the Jews escaping slavery in Egypt.The Jews were freed after Egypt was hit with plagues and the tenth plague was God kills the firstborn sons of Egypt. But he passes over or passed over the Jewish home so thereby is the name of Passover is that God passed over the Jewish homes and spared the firstborn son.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: It is celebrated nightly with Seders.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: It's celebrated the first two nights. Reformed Jews some will even do it the last two nights as well as Seder. You read a Haggadah, you learn about the escape from - from Egypt, from the bondage in Egypt. It was something I really enjoyed doing as a kid, Don.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: OK, so let's get to Easter, now. What are the favorite things candy, but is it eggs? What is it?

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Yes, so the most popular Easter candies, take a look here. Reese's peanut butter eggs number one. The Kinder chocolate candy eggs. I think we're sensing a theme here, right with chocolate eggs. How about some jelly beans? Right? That's number three. Again, chocolate eggs number four and the Cadbury Easter cream eggs, number five.So I think, I think we have a pretty good scheme going on here. Eggs are pretty big. That's what I have.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: They're weighing in over that. Does anyone remember my favorite Easter commercial? Remember the kid. Thanks, bunny.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: I love - I loved those eggs. But I'll also just note, it's also a good time to give a greeting card, right?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh my gosh, Easter is number five.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Easter's number five, Christmas is number one. But look number five is not bad at all. So maybe I'll send you an Easter card if you send me a Passover card. How about that?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: All right, that's cool. That's cool. What's your favorite Easter candy?

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Peeps?

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Candy? Uh-huh.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: No peeps.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Oh, peanut butter eggs, hello.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: No Cadbury eggs with the yolk.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Reese's Peanut butter eggs, number one baby.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Number one there you go. So Kaitlan roots for one of the best teams in college football and roots for one of the best Easter candy.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: I've got good taste. What can I say?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Oh boy. Oh boy.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thanks, that wasn't like me, not very much.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Looking at that. Avenger star Jeremy Renner is speaking out about the terrifying snowplow accident that he suffered on New Year's Day. The 52-year-old actor broke more than thirty bones when he tried to stop the vehicle from trampling his nephew. He spent several months in the hospital recovering from his injuries and he's given his first interview to Diane Sawyer and he says he remains haunted by the memory.(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP) JEREMY RENNER, ACTOR: If I was there on my own, that would have been a horrible way to die and surely I would have, surely.

utterances.speaker: DIANE SAWYER
utterances.sentences: Do you remember the pain?

utterances.speaker: RENNER
utterances.sentences: Oh, all of it. Yes, I was awake through every moment and it's - it's exactly like you imagined it would feel like. If you - it's hard to imagine what that feels like. But when you look the machine and you look at and I was on asphalt and ice. I wish I was on snow. It felt like someone took the wind out of you. Too many things are going on the body to feel pain is everything. So if your soul could have pain.(END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Your soul could have pain. Renner says he has residual pain, and there's rehabilitation but he has no regrets, he says, right? He was stepping in front rescue his nephew. That has got to be a bit of the Bourne Legacy. Aaron Cross in him, right guys?

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Glad he's OK. glad he's OK. Yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Amazing to hear him talk about that. Also today, the Masters happening in Augusta. It's the second day. One young golfer though has added something special to his swing. It's Sam Bennett's first time actually competing in the tournament. Nearly two years ago, Bennett lost his father after he suffered from early onset Alzheimer's.The golfer says he will never forget though the one piece of advice that his father gave him before he died. Don't wait to do something. Bennett got his dad's words in his own handwriting tattooed on his forearm. You can see it here on his left forearm in this photo. Bennett is certainly doing something he is now tied for sixth place in the tournament, shooting the lowest score by an amateur in 22 years. And on that note -

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: On that note.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: We know you hate this. Happy Birthday.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: We love you.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Do not open this because it's something that you wanted but you cannot open it.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: It's the greatest gift.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: So Kaitlan, Kaitlan.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thanks everyone in the control room.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Kaitlan put the kibosh on the rest of this celebration. It's going to start at nine but you'll have to look at our Instagram story.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: You're going to love this. You're going to--

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: It's amazing.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: And also, I was going to wear a 10-10, got this by the way, but I was going to wear an Alabama jersey under my - we went all around, we could not find it in Manhattan yesterday. I was in the barbershop. Tim was like walking around trying to find an Alabama jersey and we never found it.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: You guys are the best. Thank you very much. Thank you to everyone else.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: We love you.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thank you for not doing anything more because I would have hated it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Oh, that's coming now. CNN News Central is now.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: Have a great weekend.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thanks everyone. Have a good weekend.

utterances.speaker: LEMON
utterances.sentences: OK, now you got - now you got to open it.
